         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">12/12/81. ¶  ¶ Mr Bentham and yourself, dear Sir Joseph, have given the world such a magnificent work on plant genera, ¶  that it is the duty of any one to help by adding a stone to such a grand struc...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">81.12.12</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, ff. 343-4.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">12/12/81.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mr Bentham and yourself, dear Sir Joseph, have given the world such a magnificent work on plant genera,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> that it is the duty of any one to help by adding a stone to such a grand structure. From Professor Pfeffer's letter<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">W. Pfeffer to M, 26 October 1881.</p>
               </note> you will observe, that the chance exists of clearing up, after nearly 100 years, what Gaertner's genus <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Athecia">Athecia</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> may be.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to W. Thiselton-Dyer, 10 September 1881 and annotations to the letter.</p>
               </note> I think it is rubiaceous from his figure and description, and as it would need only one letter to Prof. Pfeffer, to get the loan of the two fruits (one dissected) out of Gaertner's collection, you would perhaps ask him for the loan and settle this genus, as it must interest you particularly if [rubiaceous]<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Word partially obscured by binding.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>genus <seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">
                           <name key="Athecia">Athecia</name>
                        </hi>
                     </seg> … may be <seg style="font-style: italic; ">is marked with a line in the margin.</seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Annotated at the top of the sheet</seg>: Very probably a Scaevola but if we had the fruit [stalk] it would give [much] more information than the figure does. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">There is an additional marginal annotation</seg>: p. 141 Forstera in lc 28 f 6.' [See J. Gaertner (1788-91), vol. 1, p. 141 and t. 28, fig. 6.]</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You will notice from Dr Pfeffer's letter that he is willing to send <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">me</hi>
               </seg> the two little fruits on loan; — but it would be far preferable, that they should go to <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">you</hi>
               </seg>.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Pfeffer was asked for the loan: see annotations to W. Pfeffer to M, 26 October 1881.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A few days ago, when looking on some letters of your fathers, which I selected for the collection of a great collection of auto-grams of a distinguished Lady in Italy,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Maria Negri.</p>
               </note> to whom I sent many specimen letters of celebrated men, I felt deeply touched, and wished that it had been my privilege at least once to meet Sir William. His letters, full of the kindest words and full of interest as regards <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">my</hi>
               </seg> garden, impressed me now all the more deeply, and I felt, wandering back to years long since passed, "as if I was quite young once more, and my locks were not yet grey!"<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Possibly a misquotation of N. Willis, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Saturday Afternoon</seg> (before 1835: see <seg style="font-style: italic; ">The</seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Colonist</seg> (Sydney), 17 September 1835, p. 7), collected in N. Willis (1891), p. 86:</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.8728in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3799in; color: #000000; "
                     xml:lang="en">I love to look on a scene like this,</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.8728in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3799in; color: #000000; "
                     xml:lang="en">Of wild and careless play,</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.811in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; "
                     xml:lang="en">And persuade myself that I am not old,</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.811in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; "
                     xml:lang="en">And my locks are not yet grey.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully ever</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Is not <name key="Nettoa">Nettoa</name> near <name key="Corchorus">Corchorus</name>?<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">This sentence is marked with a line, and an X in each margin.</seg>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Corchorus">Corchorus</name>
                     </seg>is characterized in Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83) vol. 1, part 1, p. 235; and <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Nettoa">Nettoa</name>
                     </seg> in the 'Addenda et corrigenda', vol 1, part 3, p 986.</p>
               </note> Is its ovary really unilocular?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mr Gregory,<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Augustus Gregory was in Melbourne attending the celebrations for the opening of a new railway line to Mordialloc (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 20 December 1881, p. 4).</p>
               </note> whose companion under "arms" I was for 17 months in tropical Australia<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">North Australian Exploring Expedition, 1855-6.</p>
               </note> stepped a few days ago suddenly into my room after 23 years!</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I never saw him since his search for Leichhardt in 1858!</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Athecia">Athecia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Corchorus">Corchorus</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Nettoa">Nettoa</name>
            </p>
         </div>
